# Repository-wide line-ending policy.
#
# Authored text files are pinned to LF on commit AND on checkout: the
# ``eol=lf`` directive on every text-pattern rule below overrides a
# contributor's local ``core.autocrlf`` setting, so a Windows working
# copy gets LF terminators regardless of how the user has configured
# their git client.  The byte counts emitted by ``stats.py`` and the
# prose-yaml validator therefore see consistent input on every host,
# and the contributor avoids producing diff noise when their editor
# happens to write CRLF.
#
# Specific patterns under ``tests/fixtures/yaml-conformance/`` keep
# the historical ``-text`` override so the LF / CRLF / mixed corpus
# fixtures preserve their byte-exact terminators on every host.  The
# ``-text`` attribute disables git's automatic line-ending conversion
# AND tells git to treat the file as binary for diff purposes.  That
# tradeoff is intentional: byte-exact preservation of the corpus
# variants matters more than diff readability for those fixtures.

# Default behaviour: detect text files automatically and store them
# with LF terminators.  Binary files stay untouched.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Authored text formats — explicit so the rule is obvious to readers
# without relying solely on auto-detection heuristics.
*.md     text eol=lf
*.yaml   text eol=lf
*.yml    text eol=lf
*.py     text eol=lf
*.sh     text eol=lf
*.json   text eol=lf
*.toml   text eol=lf
*.txt    text eol=lf

# Common binary types — never normalise.
*.png    binary
*.jpg    binary
*.jpeg   binary
*.gif    binary
*.zip    binary
*.gz     binary

# YAML 1.2.2 conformance corpus: byte-exact preservation across LF /
# CRLF / mixed variants.  These overrides MUST stay below the broader
# ``*.yaml`` rule above so the ``-text`` attribute wins.
tests/fixtures/yaml-conformance/**/*.lf.yaml    -text
tests/fixtures/yaml-conformance/**/*.crlf.yaml  -text
tests/fixtures/yaml-conformance/**/*.mixed.yaml -text
